[[Category:Ships sunk by US aircraft]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{other ships| Japanese cruiser Yahagi}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Japanese cruiser Yahagi.jpg|image_size=300px\n|Ship caption=''Yahagi'' off of [[Sasebo, Nagasaki]] in December 1943\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=[[Empire of Japan]]\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Empire of Japan|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Yahagi''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship ordered=1939 Fiscal Year\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=[[Sasebo Naval Arsenal]]\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=11 November 1941\n|Ship launched=25 October 1942\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=29 December 1943 <ref>Lacroix, ''Japanese Cruisers'', p. 794.</ref>\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship maiden voyage= \n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=20 June 1945\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=*Sunk 7 April 1945 by [[USN]] aircraft south of [[Ky\u016bsh\u016b]]\n*{{Coord|30|47|N|128|08|E}}\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Agano|cruiser}}\n|Ship displacement={{convert|6652|t|LT|lk=on|abbr=on}} (standard); {{convert|7590|t|LT|lk=on|abbr=on}} (loaded)\n|Ship length={{convert|174.5|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|15.2|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|5.63|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=*4 shaft Gihon geared turbines\n*6 Kampon boilers\n*100,000 [[Horsepower#Shaft horsepower|shp]]\n|Ship speed={{convert|35|kn|km/h|0}}\n|Ship range={{convert|6300|nmi|km|-1}} at {{convert|18|kn|km/h|0}}\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship complement=736\n|Ship time to activate=\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*[[15 cm/50 41st Year Type|6 \u00d7 152 mm Type 41 guns (3 \u00d7 2)]]\n*4 \u00d7 [[8 cm/60 98th Year Type|8cm/60 Type 98 naval gun]]s (2x2),\n*2 \u00d7 triple [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun|Type 96 25 mm AA guns]],\n*2 \u00d7 twin [[Hotchkiss M1929 machine gun|13 mm machine guns]]\n*8 \u00d7 610 mm [[torpedo tube]]s (4x2)\n*48 [[naval mine]]s\n|Ship armor=*[[Belt armor|Belt]] {{convert|60|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n*[[Deck (ship)|Deck]] {{convert|20|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship aircraft=2 x [[floatplane]]s\n|Ship aircraft facilities=1 aircraft [[Aircraft catapult#Interwar and World War II|catapult]]\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n{{nihongo|'''''Yahagi'''''|\u77e2\u77e7 }} was an {{sclass-|Agano|cruiser}} which served with the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] (IJN) during [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Jentsura  | first = Hansgeorg  | year = 1976 | title = Warships of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1869-1945  | publisher = Naval Institute Press  | isbn = 0-87021-893-X }} page 111-112</ref>\n\n==Background==\n''Yahagi'' was the third of four vessels completed in the ''Agano'' class of [[light cruiser]]s, which were intended to replace increasingly obsolete light cruisers in the Imperial Japanese Navy. Funding was authorized in the [[4th Naval Armaments Supplement Programme]] of 1939, although construction was delayed due to lack of capacity in Japanese shipyards. Like other vessels of her class, ''Yahagi'' was intended for use as the flagship of a [[destroyer]] flotilla.<ref name=Stille>Stille, '' Imperial Japanese Navy Light Cruisers 1941-45 '', pages 34-39;</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe design for the ''Agano'' class was based on technologies developed by the experimental cruiser {{ship|Japanese cruiser|Y\u016bbari||2}}, resulting in a graceful and uncluttered deck line and single smokestack.<ref name=\"Stille\" />\n\n''Yahagi'' was armed with six [[15 cm/50 41st Year Type|152 mm Type 41 guns]] in three [[gun turret]]s.<ref name=\"Stille\" /> Secondary armament included four [[8 cm/60 98th Year Type|8cm/60 Type 98 naval gun]]s designed specifically for the class, in two twin turrets amidships. Anti-aircraft weapons included two triple [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun|25 mm AA guns]] in front of the bridge, and two twin [[Hotchkiss M1929 machine gun|13 mm mounts]] near the mast.<ref name=\"Stille\" /> ''Yahagi'' also had two quadruple torpedo launchers for [[Type 93 torpedo]]es located below the flight deck, with eight reserve torpedoes.<ref name=\"Stille\" /> The torpedo tubes were mounted on the centerline, as was more common with destroyers, and had a rapid reload system. Being mounted on the centerline allowed the twin launchers to fire to either port or starboard, meaning that a full eight-torpedo broadside could be fired, whereas a ship with separate port and starboard launchers can only fire half of its torpedoes at a time. Two [[depth charge]] rails and 18 depth charges were also installed aft. ''Yahagi'' was also equipped with two [[Aichi E13A]] aircraft and had a flight deck with a 26-foot catapult.<ref name=\"Stille\" />\n\nThe engines were a quadruple-shaft geared turbine arrangement with six boilers in five boiler rooms, developing {{convert|100000|shp|abbr=on}} for a maximum speed of {{convert|35|kn|km/h}}.\n\n==Service career==\n\n===Early career===\nBuilt at [[Sasebo Naval Arsenal]], ''Yahagi'' was [[Keel laying|laid down]] on 11 November 1941, [[Ship launching|launched]] on 25 October 1942 and completed on 29 December 1943.<ref name=\"Nishida\">{{cite web |first= Hiroshi |last= Nishida |url= http://homepage2.nifty.com/nishidah/e/stc0336.htm |title= Agano-class light cruisers |year= 2002 |work= Imperial Japanese Navy |access-date= 28 September 2014 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20121208192843/http://homepage2.nifty.com/nishidah/e/stc0336.htm |archive-date= 8 December 2012 |url-status= dead }}</ref> On completion, she was assigned as flagship of Destroyer Squadron 10 of the [[IJN 3rd Fleet]]. In February 1944 she was dispatched to [[Singapore]] for training and for patrols of the [[Lingga Islands]].\n\nIn May, ''Yahagi'' departed Singapore for [[Tawi Tawi]] with the [[aircraft carrier]]s {{ship|Japanese aircraft carrier|Taih\u014d||2}}, {{ship|Japanese aircraft carrier|Zuikaku||2}} and {{ship|Japanese aircraft carrier|Sh\u014dkaku||2}} and cruisers {{ship|Japanese cruiser|My\u014dk\u014d||2}} and {{ship|Japanese cruiser|Haguro||2}} as part of Admiral [[Jisaburo Ozawa]]'s \"First Carrier Striking Force\" to oppose the American [[United States Fifth Fleet|Fifth Fleet]] in a \"decisive battle\" off [[Saipan]]. ''Yahagi'' was command ship for DesDiv 10's {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Asagumo|1938|2}}, DesDiv 17's {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Urakaze|1940|2}}, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Isokaze|1939|2}} and {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Tanikaze|1940|2}}, DesDiv 61's {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Wakatsuki||2}}, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Hatsuzuki||2}}, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Akizuki|1941|2}} and {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Shimotsuki||2}}, screening the aircraft carriers.<ref name=\"combinedfleet\">{{cite web | url = http://combinedfleet.com/yahagi_t.htm | work =Combined Fleet.com |title =  Yahagi | accessdate = 9 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Battles in the Philippines===\nThe [[Battle of the Philippine Sea]] began on 19 June 1944. The \"First Carrier Striking Force\" attacked [[USN]] [[Task Force 58]], but suffered overwhelming aircraft losses in what was latter nicknamed the \"[[Great Marianas Turkey Shoot]]\". ''Yahagi'' escaped the battle unharmed, and together with ''Urakaze'' rescued 570 crewmen from the carrier ''Sh\u014dkaku'' after it was torpedoed by {{USS|Cavalla|SS-244}}.<ref name=\"combinedfleet\" />\n\nAfter [[dry dock]] and refitting at [[Kure Naval Arsenal]] from late June to early July 1944, ''Yahagi'' was fitted with two additional triple-mount [[Type 96 25 mm AT/AA Gun]] mounts amidships (bringing its total to 48 barrels) and a Type 13 air-search and a Type 22 surface-search [[radar]] set. On 8 July 1944, ''Yahagi'' departed Kure with troops, and numerous battleships, cruisers and destroyers and returned to Singapore via Manila.<ref name=\"combinedfleet\" />\n\nOn 22 October 1944, ''Yahagi'' was in the [[Battle of Leyte Gulf]] in the Second Section of Force \"A\" of Vice Admiral [[Takeo Kurita]]'s First Mobile Striking Force: ([[Leyte Gulf order of battle#Japanese Forces 2|Center Force]]), commanding DesRon 10's DesDiv 2's {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Kiyoshimo||2}}, DesDiv 4's {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Nowaki|1940|2}} and DesDiv 17's ''Urakaze'', {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Yukikaze|1939|2}}, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Hamakaze|1940|2}} and ''Isokaze''. She was accompanied by battleships {{ship|Japanese battleship|Kong\u014d||2}} and {{ship|Japanese battleship|Haruna||2}} and cruisers {{ship|Japanese cruiser|Tone|1937|2}}, {{ship|Japanese cruiser|Chikuma|1938|2}}, {{ship|Japanese cruiser| Kumano||2}} and {{ship|Japanese cruiser|Suzuya|1934|2}}. During the [[Battle of the Sibuyan Sea]] on 24 October 1944, the fleet endured 11 raids by over 250 [[Task Force 38]] carrier aircraft from the {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}, {{USS|Essex|CV-9|2}}, {{USS|Intrepid|CV-11|2}}, {{USS|Franklin|CV-13|2}}, {{USS|Lexington|CV-16|2}} and {{USS|Cabot|CVL-28|2}}. Although the battleship {{ship|Japanese battleship|Musashi||2}} was sunk and {{ship|Japanese battleship|Yamato||2}} and {{ship|Japanese battleship|Nagato||2}} were hit, ''Yahagi'' was unscathed.<ref name=\"combinedfleet\" />\n\nLikewise in the [[Battle off Samar]] on 25 October 1944, ''Yahagi'' fought her way through the battle without damage. On 26 October 1944, Force A was attacked by 80 carrier aircraft off [[Panay]], followed by 30 [[United States Army Air Forces|USAAF]] [[B-24 Liberator]] heavy bombers and an additional 60 carrier-based aircraft. Throughout these attacks ''Yahagi'' was not hit and returned to [[Brunei]] safely.<ref name=\"combinedfleet\" />\n\n[[File:Yahagi 03.jpg|thumb|''Yahagi'' sinking]]\n\n==End of the Imperial Japanese Navy==\nOn 16 November 1944, DesRon 10 was deactivated and ''Yahagi'' was assigned as the flagship of Rear Admiral [[Keiz\u014d Komura]]'s new DesRon 2. ''Yahagi'' was ordered back to Japan on the same day for refit, returning safely to Sasebo on 24 November. She remained in Japanese home waters until March 1945.<ref name=\"combinedfleet\" />\n\nOn 6 April 1945, ''Yahagi'' received orders for \"[[Operation Ten-Go]]\", to attack the American invasion force off [[Okinawa]]. ''Yahagi'' was ordered to accompany ''Yamato'' on its final suicide mission against the American fleet. The operation also included the destroyers ''Isokaze'', ''Hamakaze'', ''Yukikaze'', {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Kasumi|1937|2}}, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Hatsushimo|1933|2}}, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Asashimo||2}}, {{ship|Japanese destroyer|Fuyutsuki||2}} and ''Suzutsuki''.<ref name=\"combinedfleet\" />\n\nAt 1220 on 7 April 1945 the ''Yamato'' force was attacked by waves of 386 aircraft (180 fighters, 75 bombers, 131 torpedo planes) from Task Force 58. [[File:Yahagi 02.jpg|225 px|thumb|right|Light cruiser ''Yahagi'' under intense bomb and torpedo attack<ref>CombinedFleet.com</ref>]]At 12:46, during the first wave, a torpedo hit ''Yahagi'' directly in her engine room, killing the entire engineering room crew and bringing her to a complete stop. Dead in the water, ''Yahagi'' was hit by at least six more torpedoes and 12 bombs by succeeding waves of air attacks.  ''Isokaze'' attempted to come to ''Yahagi''{{'}}s aid but was attacked, heavily damaged, and sank sometime later. ''Yahagi'' capsized towards her starboard side, and sank at 14:05 at {{Coord|30|47|N|128|08|E|display=inline, title}} taking 445 crewmen with her. Rear Admiral Komura and Captain [[Tameichi Hara]] were among the survivors rescued by ''Hatsushimo'' and ''Yukikaze''. Her survivors could see ''Yamato'' in the distance, still steaming south as U.S. aircraft continued their attacks. However, in reality, ''Yamato'' was only minutes away from sinking.<ref>Hara, ''Japanese Destroyer Captain'', 298.</ref> ''Yahagi'' was removed from the [[navy list]] on 20 June 1945.<ref name=\"Nishida\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book | last = Brown| first = David| authorlink = | year = 1990| title = Warship Losses of World War Two| publisher = Naval Institute Press| location = | isbn = 1-55750-914-X}}\n*{{cite book| last = Dull| first = Paul S.| authorlink = | year = 1978| chapter = | title = A Battle History of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1941-1945| publisher = Naval Institute Press| location = Annapolis, Maryland| isbn = 0-87021-097-1| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/battlehistoryofi0000dull}}\n*{{cite book | last = Feifer| first = George| year = 2001| chapter = Operation Heaven Number One| title = The Battle of Okinawa: The Blood and the Bomb| publisher = The Lyons Press| location =| isbn = 1-58574-215-5}}\n*{{cite book | last = Hara| first = Tameichi| authorlink = Tameichi Hara| year = 1961| chapter = The Last Sortie| title = Japanese Destroyer Captain| publisher = [[Ballantine Books]]| location = New York & Toronto| isbn = 978-1-59114-354-3| oclc = 255849609}} \u2014 First-hand account of the battle by the captain of the Japanese cruiser ''Yahagi''.\n* {{cite book| last = Jentschura| first = Hansgeorg| first2 = Dieter |last2=Jung|first3=Peter |last3=Mickel| year = 1977| title = Warships of the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1869\u20131945| publisher = United States Naval Institute| location = Annapolis, Maryland| isbn = 0-87021-893-X|lastauthoramp=y}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Lacroix|first1=Eric|last2=Wells II|first2=Linton |title=Japanese Cruisers of the Pacific War|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, Maryland|date=1997|isbn=0-87021-311-3 |lastauthoramp=y |authorlink2=Linton Wells II}}\n*{{cite book| last = Skulski| first = Janusz| year = 1989| title = The Battleship Yamato| publisher = Naval Institute Press| location = Annapolis, Maryland| isbn = 0-87021-019-X| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/battleshipyamato00skul}}\n*{{cite book | last = Spurr| first = Russell| year = 1995| title = [[A Glorious Way to Die|A Glorious Way to Die: The Kamikaze Mission of the Battleship Yamato, April 1945]]| publisher = Newmarket Press| location = | isbn = 1-55704-248-9}}\n*{{cite book | last = Stille | first = Mark | authorlink = | year = 2012 |  title = Imperial Japanese Navy Light Cruisers 1941-45| publisher = Osprey | location = | isbn = 1-84908-562-5 }}\n* {{cite book|last=Williams| first= Mike|title=Yahagi - One Light Cruiser at Leyte Gulf| editor=Jordan, John| publisher=Conway| location=London| date=2012|series=Warship 2012| pages=81\u201397| isbn=978-1-84486-156-9}}\n*{{cite book | last = Whitley| first = M.J.| authorlink = | coauthors = | year = 1995| chapter = | title = Cruisers of World War Two: An International Encyclopedia| publisher = Naval Institute Press| location =Annapolis, Maryland | isbn = 1-55750-141-6}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web  | url = http://combinedfleet.com/yahagi_t.htm | work =Combined fleet |title = Yahagi| accessdate = 9 February 2020}} \n* {{cite web |first= Nishida |last= Nishida |url= http://homepage2.nifty.com/nishidah/e/stc0336.htm |title= Agano-class light cruisers |year= 2002 |work= Imperial Japanese Navy |access-date= 28 September 2014 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20121208192843/http://homepage2.nifty.com/nishidah/e/stc0336.htm |archive-date= 8 December 2012 |url-status= dead }}\n\n{{Agano class cruiser}}\n{{April 1945 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yahagi}}\n[[Category:Agano-class cruisers]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Japan]]\n[[Category:1942 ships]]\n[[Category:World War II cruisers of Japan]]\n[[Category:World War II shipwrecks in the East China Sea]]\n[[Category:Cruisers sunk by aircraft]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in April 1945]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk by US aircraft]]\n", "name_user": "Cobatfor", "label": "safe",